node.text:
Male northern cardinals are famous for their funky red mohawks, but sometimes you may spot one who is bald as a coot. You could be forgiven for thinking their impressive plumage has been lost to some sort of illness, but balding is often a natural part of life for these vibrant birds.

Birds need healthy feathers in order to fly and part of maintaining them involves ditching the old to make space for the new. Usually among the songbirds this happens gradually, and so molts aren’t terribly noticeable to our eye. For some reason the cardinal opts for a different strategy, ditching all of its head feathers in one fell swoop. The drastic and rather comical transformation sees their once heavily feathered heads turned to smooth domes that show off their ear holes.

A cardinal’s bald phase usually lasts around a week before feathers begin to grow back again and within a month they’ll be back to their former, punky selves. Rock on, you crazy cardinals.

Image credit: Bonnie Taylor Barry / Danita Delimont / Shutterstock

node.text:
A rare fossil that has frozen almost an entire beetle in time was found, after much consideration, to be a new-to-science species of frog-legged beetle. Retrieved from what was once the Eocene Green River Formation in northwest Colorado, the arresting specimen has been dubbed Pulchritudo attenboroughi, or Attenborough’s Beauty, approximately 49 million years after its demise. It’s a great honor for any naturalist to have a species named after them, and while David Attenborough may already have a few under his belt, his latest addition is a real beauty. 

What’s perhaps most remarkable about the specimen is its near-perfect preservation. Beetles are tough critters with some extant species being able to survive being run over by a tank, but generally speaking, they rarely star in the best fossils. After it expired, P attenboroughi took to the waters of the Eocene Green River Formation before sinking into the sediment. While most beetles tend to come apart at this stage, with their remains being preserved as individual wing cases, this particular dead beetle held true.
​
​Credit: ©Denver Museum of Nature & Science

Scientists from the Boston University Schools of Medicine and Public Health have developed machine learning methods that are capable of identifying and characterizing metabolism-disrupting chemicals. Their research is published in Environmental Health Perspectives.
​
​Sitting on your sofa too much might make you gain weight. Sounds like a statement of common sense, right? However, weight gain might not solely be a result of adopting an overly sedentary lifestyle. Rather, it could be caused by exposure to certain chemicals that might be present in your furniture.
​

Get a load of this silky bag of funnel-web spiders being carefully pried open with some tweezers. This was the very first egg sac to have been bred in captivity, resulting in over 100 baby funnels entering the mortal realm at the Australian Reptile Park. The achievement was excellent news for the park’s antivenom program, as they intend to milk 3,000 funnel webs every year so the venom can be used to create antivenom that could treat and save the lives of unfortunate spider bite victims. 

Video credit: @australianreptilepark

node.text:
Black Fall, or ‘Svartifoss’, is a waterfall surrounded by columns of hexagonal black basalt rock in southern Iceland. Long ago, violent eruptions of lava cooled and created these stunning geological formations in a process known as ‘columnar jointing’. The Giant’s Causeway in Northern Ireland is another of the world’s breathtaking examples of columnar jointing.
​ 
Credits: HandmadePictures / MichaelMou85 / Matteo Provendola / Shutterstock

node.text:
Say hello to my little friend. This wee chap is a hermit crab, a member of the superfamily Paguroidea who live inside empty sea shells. They can be found scuttling across coastal regions and as deep in the ocean as 150m. Hermit crabs like to hang out in big colonies and even sleep piled on top of each other. Loving that slumber party life!

The empty sea shells that they live in are mostly shells of whelks and periwinkles, and they upscale into larger shells shed by other organisms as they get older. Moving house is a stressful business for these animals as without a shell they risk being very vulnerable. Sometimes hermit crabs will attempt to steal other hermit crabs' shells by either dragging out the owner with force, or by knocking on a shell it wants which challenges the owner to a duel. The crab left standing takes the shell, like GTA - but with crustaceans.

Image credit: JetKat / Gialdini Luca / Shutterstock.

For #MicrobeMonday we’re taking a look at some diatoms captured on camera at 1000 x magnification. These single-celled organisms have an outer wall made of silica which is the same chemical compound found in glass. Here, we see them in colonies of four forming miniature X formations as they float around. To give you an idea of just how many of these little guys live in water across the globe, it’s thought they produce around 20% of Earth’s total oxygen via photosynthesis. Incredible!

Video courtesy of @jam_and_germs

node.text:
Ever looked at your cat and wondered, “My, what ridiculously enormous pupils you have?” It can be quite mesmerizing, if not a little terrifying, to look on as the once-slender black slits in their eyes blow and contract, but why do they do it?

Pupil size in many species reacts to light and dark, which is why our pupils look bigger at night compared to in the day. This is an adaptive response and it enables us to take in more and less light so that we can continue to see even as the environment changes.

For hunting cats, blown pupils are a way of gleaning as much information as possible before launching yourself on your unsuspecting prey and, if needs be, giving chase. As cats have grown domesticated, this “prey” has transformed from small, flitting rodents to that sparkly prawn plushy you wave in front her on a piece of string. Regardless of the target, the behavior makes it easier for cats to slam down those murder mittens on their intended victim. 

Happy #InternationalCatDay, you cool cats and kittens.

Image credit: Anamaria Todor / Shutterstock.com

Fancy a swim? This is Lake Hillier on Middle Island, Australia.
​
​Microorganisms, such as Dunaliella salina, cause the high salt content in the lake to produce a red dye, as well as a red salt-loving bacteria present in the salt crusts, which contribute to the strange pink color. The lake is safe to swim in despite its unusual color.

node.text:
This is a male Mwanza flat-headed rock agama (Agama mwanzae), which can be found scrabbling around in Tanzania, Rwanda, and Kenya. It sometimes gets confused for the equally beautiful red-headed rock agama, whose Latin name is an easy one to remember (Agama agama).

They are sexually dimorphic so only the males are vividly colored, while the females are mottled and brown. The males are known for trying to catch the eye of potential mates by doing a sexy head-bobbing dance. 

As two tonal animals that are very good at climbing rocks, it’s perhaps unsurprising that the males have earnt the species the nickname “Spider-Man”.
